#8.8 Exercises – Problem 7
aus_production %>%
  autoplot(Gas)

print("multiplicative seasonality is necessary as the seasonal variations are not constant through the series. They are changing proportional to the level of the series.")
## [1] "multiplicative seasonality is necessary as the seasonal variations are not constant through the series. They are changing proportional to the level of the series."
fit <- aus_production %>%
  model(add = ETS(Gas ~ error("A") + trend("A") + season("A")),
        multiplicative = ETS(Gas ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("M")))
aus_production %>%
   model(add = ETS(Gas ~ error("A") + trend("A") + season("A")),
        multiplicative = ETS(Gas ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("M"))) %>%
   forecast(h=24) %>%
  autoplot(aus_production)

#Experiment with making the trend damped

fit2 <- aus_production %>%
  model(damp = ETS(Gas  ~ error("M") + trend("Ad", phi = 0.9) + season("M")))
fit2 %>%
  forecast(h = 24) %>%
  autoplot(aus_production)

print("making the trend damped does not appear to improve the forecast")
## [1] "making the trend damped does not appear to improve the forecast"

#9.11 Exercises – Problem 2
amazon <- gafa_stock %>%
  filter(Symbol=="AMZN")

amazon %>%
  autoplot(Close) +
  labs(title="Closing Stock Price ($USD)") 

print("As seen by the plot, the series is not stationalry in either mean or variance. There is a clear  trend and changing levels that appears to vary over time, indicating that the series is non-stationary and require differencing to achieve stationarity.")
## [1] "As seen by the plot, the series is not stationalry in either mean or variance. There is a clear  trend and changing levels that appears to vary over time, indicating that the series is non-stationary and require differencing to achieve stationarity."
amazon %>%
ACF(Close) %>%
autoplot()
## Warning: Provided data has an irregular interval, results should be treated with
## caution. Computing ACF by observation.

print("As seen by the ACF plot, there is a gradual decrease in autocorrelation as the lag increases. This indicates that there is some correlation between observations that are further apart in time, which suggests that the mean and/or variance of the series is changing over time. Thus series is not stationary")
## [1] "As seen by the ACF plot, there is a gradual decrease in autocorrelation as the lag increases. This indicates that there is some correlation between observations that are further apart in time, which suggests that the mean and/or variance of the series is changing over time. Thus series is not stationary"
amazon %>%
PACF(Close) %>%
autoplot()
## Warning: Provided data has an irregular interval, results should be treated with
## caution. Computing ACF by observation.

print("he PACF shows very strong autocorrelation for 1-day lag, meaning that there is very strong autocorrelation between one closing price and the closing price of the previous day.")
## [1] "he PACF shows very strong autocorrelation for 1-day lag, meaning that there is very strong autocorrelation between one closing price and the closing price of the previous day."
print("The PACF plot shows that there is correlation between stock price and their 1 lagged value, autocorrelation betweenclosing price and the closing price of the previous day. This suggests that there may be a trend or a seasonality present in the series. We also see a sinusoidal pattern which indicates the presence of seasonality. This means that the series is not stationary, as a stationary time series should not exhibit any trends or seasonality.  ")
## [1] "The PACF plot shows that there is correlation between stock price and their 1 lagged value, autocorrelation betweenclosing price and the closing price of the previous day. This suggests that there may be a trend or a seasonality present in the series. We also see a sinusoidal pattern which indicates the presence of seasonality. This means that the series is not stationary, as a stationary time series should not exhibit any trends or seasonality.  "

data(pelt)
hare <- pelt %>% select("Year", "Hare")
lynx<- pelt %>% select("Year", "Lynx")

## Part a Produce a time plot of the time series.
pelt %>% select("Year", "Hare") %>% autoplot(.vars=Hare) +
  labs(title = "Hare Trades") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

##Additionally, to also look at trades of Lynx fur, here is the plot
pelt %>% select("Year", "Lynx") %>% autoplot(.vars=Lynx) +
  labs(title = "Lynx Trades") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

##Part b 
arima_fit <- pelt %>%
  model(ARIMA(Hare)) %>%
  report(arima_fit)

#The autoregressive, differencing, and moving average parts of the model,are represented by the notation (p, d, q). 

#Here,
#p = 2-> model includes two autoregressive terms (AR(2)).
#d = 0-> model does not include any differencing.
#q = 1-> model includes one moving average term (MA(1)).

##Part e

# Fitting the ARIMA model
arima_fit2 <- Arima(hare$Hare, order = c(4, 0, 0))

##Here, we are using the ARIMA model as in part b.
##Hence, the model has order P=4|D=0|Q=0.
##It is an autoregressive model with 4 lagged autoregressive terms and a constant term.

# Generate forecast for next 3 years
armia_forecast <- forecast(arima_fit2, h = 3)

# Print the forecasts
print(armia_forecast)
